The bubbles that were present when you cracked the bottle were not vacuum bubbles. That's a process called "deaeration".

The force of the vacuum was removing the oxygen (and other dissolved gases) from the water.

The process is most commonly used to remove air from water being provided to steam boilers or steam turbines. This reduces differential pressures and produces what is called "low-pressure steam". The process is also used in medical equipment such as dialysis machines where water is a primary component of the dialysate fluid. This prevents air bubbles from forming on the fibers of the dialyzer and results in better filtration for the patient.
